<p><b>Codex Sinaiticus</b> (Shelfmarks and references: London, <a href="/wiki/British_Library" title="British Library">Brit. Libr.</a>, Additional 43725; <a href="/wiki/Biblical_manuscript#Gregory-Aland" title="Biblical manuscript">Gregory-Aland</a> nº <big><b>א</b></big> (Aleph) or <b>01</b>, (<a href="/wiki/Biblical_manuscript#Von_Soden" title="Biblical manuscript">Soden</a> δ 2) is one of the most important hand-written ancient copies of the <a href="/wiki/Koine_Greek" title="Koine Greek">Greek</a> <a href="/wiki/Bible" title="Bible">Bible</a>. It was written in the 4th century, in <a href="/wiki/Uncial" title="Uncial" class="mw-redirect">uncial</a> letters. It came to the attention of scholars in the 19th century at the <a href="/wiki/Saint_Catherine%27s_Monastery,_Mount_Sinai" title="Saint Catherine's Monastery, Mount Sinai">Greek Monastery of Mount Sinai</a>, with further material discovered in the 20th century, and most of it is today in the <a href="/wiki/British_Library" title="British Library">British Library</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Aland_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Aland-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Originally it contained the whole of both Testaments. The <a href="/wiki/Greek_Old_Testament" title="Greek Old Testament" class="mw-redirect">Greek Old Testament</a> (or <i>Septuagint</i>) survived almost complete, along with a complete <a href="/wiki/New_Testament" title="New Testament">New Testament</a>, plus the <a href="/wiki/Epistle_of_Barnabas" title="Epistle of Barnabas">Epistle of Barnabas</a>, and portions of <a href="/wiki/The_Shepherd_of_Hermas" title="The Shepherd of Hermas">The Shepherd of Hermas</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Aland_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Aland-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
